\begin_layout Subsection

The PCA Formulation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

A supernova spectrum is expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{s_{i}}(\lambda)$
\end_inset

. We claim that this spectrum can be well represented by a reconstructed spectrum 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{r_{i}}(\lambda)$
\end_inset

 which is the sum of the mean spectrum and 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 weighted principal component spectra as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \[\vec{s_{i}}(\lambda) \approx \vec{r_{i,m}}(\lambda) = \vec{\mu}(\lambda) + \sum_{j=1}^{m} c_{ij} \vec{\xi_{j}}(\lambda)\]
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

where 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 refers to a particular supernova, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\mu}(\lambda)$
\end_inset

 is the mean spectrum, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\xi_{j}}(\lambda)$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

th principal component spectrum (PCS), and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{ij}$
\end_inset

 is the real weight.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection

The Principal Component Spectrum
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

To find the principal component spectrum (PCS) we need to calculate the correlation of the fluxes at each wavelength in order to see how different parts of the spectrum are related. We compute a correlations matrix with elements:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \[  \textbf{R}(\lambda_{m},\lambda_{n}) = \frac{1}{N-1} \sum_{i=1}^{N} \frac{[\vec{s}_{i}(\lambda_{m}) - \vec{\mu}(\lambda_{m})][\vec{s}_{i}(\lambda_{n}) - \vec{\mu}(\lambda_{n})]}{\sigma(\lambda_{m})\sigma(\lambda_{n})} \]
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

where 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is the total number of spectra used in the analysis, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{n}$
\end_inset

 are the standard deviation of the flux in the wavelength bins corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{n}$
\end_inset

 respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

We then calculate the covariance matrix with elements:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \[ \textbf{V}(\lambda_{m},\lambda_{n}) = \frac{1}{N-1} \sum_{i=1}^{N} [\vec{s}_{i}(\lambda_{m}) - \vec{\mu}(\lambda_{m})][\vec{s}_{i}(\lambda_{n}) - \vec{\mu}(\lambda_{n})] \]
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

We can then find the principal components by decomposing the covariance matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{V}$
\end_inset

 into the product of the orthonormal matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{P}$
\end_inset

 which consists of our eigenvectors, and the diagonal matrix 
